  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Implementation of the interagency Telecommunications Security Standards (TESS) project in the Central African Republic (C.A.R)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Central African Republic (C.A.R.) is a land-locked country afflicted by successive waves of conflicts, high numbers of vulnerable populations in dire need of humanitarian assistance, as well as infrastructure challenges. In many intervention areas, emergency operations as well as humanitarian actors&#x2019; safety and coordination efforts, are hampered by inadequate telecommunications systems. Yet, the ability to communicate with the country security department is vital to all humanitarian operations, particularly for supporting the safety and security of staff in the field.

The inter-agency assessment mission conducted by the Telecommunications Security Standards (TESS) in February 2019 resulted in a set of recommendations to upgrade and improve the standardization of radio rooms for humanitarian operations in C.A.R. The main objective of the proposed project is to expand radio room facilities in 15 locations across C.A.R using the standards adopted by the UN security management team. These standards will be the same in each location with the following telecommunications systems in place:

 A dedicated UN channel for use by all UN staff to communicate with the UNDSS radio room for any security communication needs across 15 locations
 A dedicated NGO channel for use by all NGO staff to communicate with UNDSS for any security communication needs across 15 locations
 A dedicated mobile satellite phone number in place in all radio rooms to facilitate field vehicle missions. There is a need to be able to communicate with radio rooms at any time in cases when mobile HF radio is not working or not present in the vehicle
 A dedicated local mobile phone number in place in all radio rooms, to be used for any security communications with radio rooms and UN staff
 Define a standard radio programming code for humanitarians to be able to use Very High Frequency and High Frequency (VHF/HF) handheld radios and base stations.

The TESS project will improve communications among humanitarian staff in the field, as they conduct lifesaving work in challenging environments. This will facilitate emergency operations and enable stakeholders to be informed about access and security issues ahead of time.</narrative>
  </description>
